@flexiarg ukrns/separate-direct-indirect-and-out-of-scope-levers
@title Separate Direct, Indirect, and Out-of-Scope Levers (Sketch)
@verdict early
@keywords sketch, leverage, direct, indirect, out-of-scope, honesty, service-design, institutional-conditions
@audience UKRN Services design, funders, institutional leads, board readers
@tone analytic-foundational
@style sketch
@references [system-coherence/separate-configurable-choices-from-load-bearing-couplings writing-coherence/plain-language-thesis]
@summary A service-level design becomes more credible when it states which conditions it can move directly, which only indirectly, and which fall outside its practical reach.

! conclusion: Not every institutional condition is equally movable by a network service. A design that types its own levers is more honest, more governable, and easier to evaluate than one that implies uniform control.

  + context: The current paper's design section already distinguishes between conditions UKRN Services can move by contract or routine, conditions it can influence only through evidence and pressure, and conditions that remain prior constraints.

  + IF:
    The pattern operates on the axis: undifferentiated influence claim ↔ typed leverage claim.

  + HOWEVER:
    Real costs: typing leverage narrows the design's apparent power and exposes where it depends on action by others.

  + THEN:
    Name the direct levers, the indirect levers, and the out-of-scope conditions explicitly, and keep the out-of-scope ones visible in later verification.
